page.text: S e r v i c e s
Vanasse Hangen Brustlin, Inc. (VHB) has prepared this memorandum to provide responses to the
traffic comments submitted in the Fay, Spofford, Thorndike (FST) comment letter on the Proposed
Outpatient Care Facility at 620 Washington Street Traffic Impact and Access Study (TIAS), dated
November 9, 2007 and traffic comments from the town staff. FST has previously reviewed the
project during the Town of Winchester’s Town Meeting review process, after which the Town of
Winchester approved the site for re-zoning. FST’s comments provided during the re-zoning process
were addressed in the November 2007 TIAS.
Additionally, the Proponent’s development team met with FST engineers and town staff on
November 15, 2007 to discuss VHB’s preliminary responses to traffic related comments. The
responses contained in this memorandum pertain to the outstanding issues identified by FST and
town staff. This memorandum paraphrases each comment, in italics, and provides responses in a
format consistent with that used in the FST comment letter.

text.i: Comment 1: An evaluation of the intersections of Forest Street at Cross Street and Forest Street at Highland

page.text: Response 1: The intersections included in the TIAS study area were originally identified with the
input of the Winchester Engineering Department. Based on this input, all critical intersections
identified in proximity to the site were included in the TIAS. The adequacy of the study area was
confirmed by FST in their comment letter dated April 19, 2007 (submitted during the project’s re-
zoning application review), which states that “the VHB Study area adequately includes all major
intersection[s] that will be affected.” However, based on continued requests from the town staff, an
evaluation of the projected operations at the two requested additional intersections has been
Turning movement count data was collected at both of the requested intersections in
November 2007, on a typical weekday when schools were in session and no known traffic related
incidents, that could affect traffic flow patterns, occurred in the area. Data were collected during the
weekday morning and evening peak periods (7:00-9:00 AM and 4:00-6:00 PM, respectively).
November data is typically higher than annual average conditions and therefore no further seasonal
adjustments were applied to the data. The traffic count data is included in the attachments to this
memorandum. It should be noted that Highland Avenue and Sawmill Brook Road forms two
closely spaced offset intersections, and therefore, the two were analyzed as two separate
Existing traffic volumes and future traffic volume projections for the additional analysis locations
were calculated using the same methodologies and assumptions used in the November 2007 TIAS.
Traffic volume networks showing the existing and future traffic volume projections are also
included in the attachments to this memorandum.

text.i: Comment 2: Updated conceptual design plans for the proposed improvements at the Washington Street/Forest
Street and Washington Street/site driveway intersections should be provided to definitively verify the existence
of sufficient public rights-of-way to accomplish these improvements without land takings or permanent

page.text: Response 2: Updated conceptual design plans for the proposed improvement measures, based on
recent detailed survey of Washington Street, confirm that the proposed improvement measures at
both the Washington Street/Forest Street and Washington Street/northern site driveway
intersections can be accomplished within existing rights-of-way or property controlled by the
Proponent. These updated conceptual design plans are included in the attachments to this
memorandum. Final detailed design plans for both intersections will be submitted to the town
during later stages of project permitting.

text.i: Comment 3: During the Development Agreement review process, it was indicated that the site driveway
garage exit is located in an awkward location for existing traffic.

page.text: Response 3: As discussed during the November 15, 2007 meeting with town staff, the Proponent will
investigate the provision of an electronic gate to prohibit vehicles within the garage from exiting via
this driveway during critical periods (likely weekday afternoons), along with appropriate internal

text.i: Comment 4: A discussion of the relative benefits between the two potential improvement plans for the Cross
Street/Holton Street/East Street/Lowell Avenue intersection should be provided.

page.text: Response 4: Two potential improvement concepts for the Cross Street/Holton Street/East
Street/Lowell Avenue intersection were included in the TIAS. As suggested by the Town of
Winchester’s traffic peer review consultant during the re-zoning application review process for this
project, the concepts provide two different options for restricting vehicular access to East Street, with
the intention of reducing cut-through traffic along East Street:
Concept 1: a localized one-way eastbound travel restriction on East Street at Holton Street
would prohibit all westbound traffic from accessing East Street at this location.
Concept 2: access to East Street at this intersection would be eliminated through construction
of a dead-end on East Street, with provision for emergency vehicle access only.
The primary difference between the two proposed concepts is the proposal to only partially restrict
vehicular access to/from East Street under Concept 1 vs. entirely prohibiting vehicular access under
Concept 2. Therefore, while both concepts would be expected to result in some diversion of
commuter vehicles to other residential streets (likely to the west of the Cross Street/Holton
Street/East Street/Lowell Street intersection) the Concept 2 design would be expected to result in a
greater magnitude of diversions. Emergency vehicle access to East Street could be maintained under
the Concept 2 design through the use of a breakaway gate for emergency vehicles only.
Additionally, based on the greater restriction of access to and from East Street, the Concept 2 design
would likely result in a reduction in overall turning movement activity at the Cross Street/Holton
Street/East Street/Lowell Street intersection. Therefore, the Concept 2 design is likely to result in
slightly improved overall operations at the intersection, as compared to the Concept 1 design.
It should be noted that any improvement measures requested by the neighborhood residents will
ultimately be subject to the Town of Winchester’s review processes and approval by the Winchester

text.i: Comment 5: A discussion of the relative benefits of the proposed potential traffic-calming improvements in the
Brookside Avenue and Sunset Road neighborhoods should be provided. It should be noted that Winchester
does not currently have a ‘residential parking’ program.

page.text: Response 5: The Proponent met with the residents of the Brookside Avenue and Sunset Road
neighborhoods to discuss potential traffic-calming measures to reduce speeds and cut-through
traffic in these neighborhoods as presented in the TIAS. While the issues encountered by each
neighborhood differ somewhat, the residents have generally expressed the following priorities and
provision of measures which reduce vehicle speed and/or discourage commuter vehicle
travel within the residential neighborhoods should be considered; and
ideally, the residents would prefer not to implement structural improvements, such as
traffic-calming circles or curb extensions, which may physically alter or prohibit existing
Based on the initial feedback from these meetings, the Proponent is currently updating the
improvement proposals to reflect resident comments and suggestions. These updated proposals will
be presented to the individual neighborhoods at future public meetings to foster further discussion
of the potential benefits or detriments associated with each set of proposals. The primary goal of the
public meeting process will be to achieve consensus on a “neighborhood preferred” set of
improvements. However, it should be noted that any improvement measures requested by the
neighborhood residents will ultimately be subject to the Town of Winchester’s review processes and
approval by the Winchester Board of Selectmen.
As previously indicated to Town staff, during the public meeting process the potential resident-only
parking restrictions suggested in the past have been deemed unnecessary. Therefore, resident-only
parking signage and other restrictions will not be included in future concepts.

text.i: Comment 6: Discussion and analysis of the proposed impacts from the proposed Tri-Community
Bikeway/Greenway should be included in the Future Conditions analysis; 25% design plans have been
submitted to MHD for this project.

page.text: Response 6: The Proponent has recently received and preliminarily reviewed the 25% design plans
for the Tri-Community Bikeway/Greenway. The bikeway plans currently indicate that the
proposed bikeway, which is located along the southern site frontage, will terminate at Washington
Street and at this point the path will “begin on-road bike route” on Washington Street north into the
City of Woburn. The Proponent intends to continue working with the Town of Winchester to
integrate an appropriate accommodation for bicyclists and pedestrians using the Tri-Community
Bikeway/Greenway into the off-site design plans.
